WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:05.600
<v Speaker 1>So some adjectives will exclusively go with star.

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:09.120
<v Speaker 1>Some adjectives will exclusively go with ser.

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:17.360
<v Speaker 1>Some adjectives can go with either ser or estar and change their meaning like aburrido meaning bored

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:25.040
<v Speaker 1>as a state or boring as a characteristic, just changing depending on whether it goes with ser or estar.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.280
<v Speaker 1>Another example of a word like this is listo, listo

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:30.860
<v Speaker 2>Listo.

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:34.940
<v Speaker 1>Now listo when it comes with estar means ready.

00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:37.260
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I am ready?

00:00:37.739 --> 00:00:39.100
<v Speaker 2>Estoy listo.

00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:41.500
<v Speaker 2>Or lista in my case.

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:44.079
<v Speaker 1>Estoy lista or listo.

00:00:44.079 --> 00:00:46.480
<v Speaker 1>How would you say we are ready?

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:49.120
<v Speaker 2>Estamos listos.

00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:49.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:52.079
<v Speaker 1>And what if we were a female group?

00:00:52.580 --> 00:00:54.260
<v Speaker 2>Estamos listos.

00:00:54.260 --> 00:00:55.460
<v Speaker 1>Estamos listos.

00:00:55.460 --> 00:01:00.020
<v Speaker 1>And what if we wanted to emphasize we are ready?

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.680
<v Speaker 1>Somos no You make it a characteristic and it's more empathic.

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:10.200
<v Speaker 1>This isn't a very interesting idea.

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:13.160
<v Speaker 2>It's what you said when I go to fast

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:20.220
<v Speaker 1>There's a contradiction there.

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:22.700
<v Speaker 2>Nosotras estamos listas.

00:01:22.700 --> 00:01:25.580
<v Speaker 1>Yes, or female group, nosotras estamos list

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:30.400
<v Speaker 1>Mail or mix group, nosotros estamos listos.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:35.200
<v Speaker 1>So to be listo, to be ready as a characteristic.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:38.640
<v Speaker 1>means to be smart in Spanish.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:44.880
<v Speaker 1>So this is one of the words that we can use with ser or estar and the meaning changes

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:47.760
<v Speaker 1>So estoy listo, I am ready.

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:50.000
<v Speaker 1>Soy listo, I am smart.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.800
<v Speaker 1>So if you want to say he's smart, he is smart, how would you say it?

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:56.480
<v Speaker 1>Es listo.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:57.280
<v Speaker 1>Es listo.

00:01:57.280 --> 00:01:58.960
<v Speaker 1>She is smart.

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:01.120
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:06.480
<v Speaker 1>You are smart speaking informally to a woman.

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:10.960
<v Speaker 1>If you forgot the you are, you can think of where are you from that might help you trigger it.

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:12.560
<v Speaker 2>Then on the Eris

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:14.459
<v Speaker 2>Eres lista.

00:02:14.459 --> 00:02:14.700
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:16.860
<v Speaker 1>You are very smart.

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:18.780
<v Speaker 2>Eres muy lista.

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:19.739
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:19.739 --> 00:02:25.340
<v Speaker 1>The word for soul, like I'm so bored or I'm so tired is tan.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:32.140
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I'm so tired?

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:34.620
<v Speaker 2>Estoy tan cansado.

00:02:34.620 --> 00:02:35.500
<v Speaker 2>Cansada.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:36.140
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:38.540
<v Speaker 1>Estoy tan cansado.

00:02:38.540 --> 00:02:41.020
<v Speaker 1>Estoy tan cansada.

00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:41.900
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:41.940 --> 00:02:46.260
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I am so bold?

00:02:49.459 --> 00:02:50.019
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:02:54.180 --> 00:03:00.260
<v Speaker 1>How would you say he is so bold?

00:03:00.260 --> 00:03:03.140
<v Speaker 2>El esta tan aburrido.

00:03:03.140 --> 00:03:03.540
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:10.780
<v Speaker 1>Now how would you say it is so boring?

00:03:10.780 --> 00:03:11.900
<v Speaker 1>It is so boring.

00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:13.659
<v Speaker 1>So boring, not bored.

00:03:13.659 --> 00:03:15.579
<v Speaker 1>Boring.

00:03:15.579 --> 00:03:17.659
<v Speaker 2>Es tan aburrido.

00:03:17.659 --> 00:03:17.980
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:20.140
<v Speaker 1>Es tan aburrido.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:23.620
<v Speaker 1>The word for good in Spanish is bueno.

00:03:23.780 --> 00:03:25.220
<v Speaker 1>We've mentioned this before.

00:03:25.220 --> 00:03:33.060
<v Speaker 1>We have in English bon appetit, which is of course French, but we say it in English, and you can see the O of bon appetit.

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:35.860
<v Speaker 1>Splitting to become bueno in Spanish.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:41.220
<v Speaker 1>Now the meaning of bueno changes as well between ser and the star.

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:46.240
<v Speaker 1>If you're talking about it is, the change is a kind of change in feeling.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:48.240
<v Speaker 1>Es bueno, esta bueno.

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:50.800
<v Speaker 1>A small change in feeling which really depends on dialect.

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:52.320
<v Speaker 1>So we won't look at it too much here.

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:53.840
<v Speaker 1>You will just listen.

00:03:53.340 --> 00:04:02.780
<v Speaker 1>But if you refer to people, in most dialects if we use sir, we get the meaning of to be a good person or to be good at something.

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:05.340
<v Speaker 1>So if you want to say they are good

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:09.799
<v Speaker 1>And you mean they are good people or that they're good at something?

00:04:09.799 --> 00:04:11.480
<v Speaker 1>How would you say it?

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:13.720
<v Speaker 1>Son buenos.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:14.840
<v Speaker 1>Son buenos.

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:15.799
<v Speaker 1>He is good

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:24.400
<v Speaker 1>Now if you use a star, it will sound like he's attractive, he's in good form.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:29.919
<v Speaker 1>So bueno with a star, if we're talking about people, then gives you this meaning

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:31.280
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say that?

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:36.240
<v Speaker 1>He is good, meaning attractive, in good form.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:37.600
<v Speaker 2>Está bueno.

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:38.960
<v Speaker 1>Está bueno.

00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:47.800
<v Speaker 1>So you see that uh you can have many different changes in shade of meaning between ser and the star.

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:52.200
<v Speaker 1>So other than the fact that we are being permitted and obliged

00:04:52.539 --> 00:05:04.300
<v Speaker 1>To perceive and express the world in a certain way by Spanish, which is very interesting in itself, we also get the opportunity to use these different nuances

00:05:04.539 --> 00:05:06.300
<v Speaker 1>Between ser and the star.

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:13.259
<v Speaker 1>And when you really get your head around it, which is just through listening and observing and seeing how people are using it.

00:05:13.139 --> 00:05:16.100
<v Speaker 1>you will probably feel that it's missing in English.

00:05:16.100 --> 00:05:22.419
<v Speaker 1>That sometimes in English you might want to clarify not established and you can't do it.

00:05:22.419 --> 00:05:25.139
<v Speaker 1>So you realize that Spanish gives you a tool

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:31.479
<v Speaker 1>To relate to reality that in this case English doesn't give you.

00:05:31.479 --> 00:05:37.720
<v Speaker 1>And this is one of the most fascinating and exciting things about language learning, not an obstacle

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:39.140
<v Speaker 1>to speaking the language.

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:40.580
<v Speaker 1>We don't want to see it like this.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:46.820
<v Speaker 1>Oh, every time I used to be, I have to think about this characteristic or state business.

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:51.860
<v Speaker 1>No, we want to look at it from the other angle, about what it offers us.

00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:55.540
<v Speaker 1>How would you say I want to know how he is?

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:59.140
<v Speaker 1>And we mean I want to know how is he doing?

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:04.360
<v Speaker 1>How is he doing?

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:06.440
<v Speaker 2>Oh, como está?

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:07.240
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:09.240
<v Speaker 1>Quiero saber como está.

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:10.520
<v Speaker 1>Now what would it mean?

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:12.440
<v Speaker 1>Quiero saber como es.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:14.200
<v Speaker 1>What would that mean?

00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:16.740
<v Speaker 2>How he is, what he's like.

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:17.540
<v Speaker 1>Exactly.

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:19.540
<v Speaker 1>I want to know what he's like.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:20.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:25.540
<v Speaker 1>Another adjective you can use with ser or star is felice.

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:28.340
<v Speaker 1>What do you think felice might mean?

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:30.280
<v Speaker 2>Happy.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:31.960
<v Speaker 1>And how do you know that?

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:33.240
<v Speaker 2>Feliz Navidad.

00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:34.280
<v Speaker 1>Oh okay.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:35.800
<v Speaker 1>Happy Christmas.

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:37.000
<v Speaker 1>Feliz Navidad.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.240
<v Speaker 1>But is there some connection in English that might might have helped you as well?

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:44.120
<v Speaker 1>Did you hear felicity in English?

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:44.680
<v Speaker 2>Yes.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:48.120
<v Speaker 1>How would felicity be in in Spanish?

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:49.640
<v Speaker 2>Felicidad.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.120
<v Speaker 1>Felicidad, which means happiness.

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:53.560
<v Speaker 1>Happiness.

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:55.660
<v Speaker 1>So felice, happy.

00:06:55.660 --> 00:07:04.300
<v Speaker 1>So felice can also go with ser o estar to give the meaning of I'm happy or I'm a happy person.

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:08.520
<v Speaker 1>So we don't need to say I'm a happy person, we can just use sir.

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:12.759
<v Speaker 1>So like I said, there's no real way for you to know that other than listening.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:20.040
<v Speaker 1>If you wanted to play safe and say literally I'm a happy person, it would not be at all incorrect.

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:24.440
<v Speaker 1>So, firstly, how do you say I am happy as a state?

00:07:25.419 --> 00:07:26.620
<v Speaker 1>Estoy feliz.

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:27.580
<v Speaker 1>Estoy feliz.

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:31.259
<v Speaker 1>Now I'm happy and you mean as a characteristic.

00:07:31.259 --> 00:07:32.220
<v Speaker 1>Soy feliz.

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:33.099
<v Speaker 1>Soy feliz.

00:07:33.099 --> 00:07:34.940
<v Speaker 1>So this is fine, you can do this.

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:38.220
<v Speaker 1>But there's no real way for you to know whether

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:42.960
<v Speaker 1>Felis is an adjective that's flexible enough to be used with ser and the star.

00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:48.960
<v Speaker 1>It really depends on the adjective itself, the word itself, rather than the meaning in many cases.

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:51.040
<v Speaker 1>So with that insecurity

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:59.260
<v Speaker 1>And wanting to give the meaning, you could have just said, I am a happy person, and then you don't have to worry about it.

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:01.020
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say that?

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:04.040
<v Speaker 2>Soy una persona feliz.

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:04.440
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:05.720
<v Speaker 1>Soy una persona feliz.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:07.320
<v Speaker 1>And that's also perfect Spanish.

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:10.920
<v Speaker 1>So there you could have said soy feliz or soy una persona feliz.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:21.620
<v Speaker 1>So to really get our heads around SER and the star, it's important to listen actively and to notice and see how people are using SER and the star

00:08:22.039 --> 00:08:30.440
<v Speaker 1>and making our own conclusions as to why working with this base of state and characteristic.

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:31.979
<v Speaker 1>It's a process of listening.

00:08:31.979 --> 00:08:41.820
<v Speaker 1>And the more you get intimate with this idea, it offers you a great range of expression that you don't have in English, and you should really enjoy it.

